---
import LightLayout from '../../../layouts/LightLayout.astro';
---

<LightLayout title="Script · YouTube" description="Structured script by blocks for Stripe Product Sense.">

  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-12 pb-6">
    <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← Back to hub</a>

    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mt-6 mb-4">
      <span class="text-5xl">📺</span>
      <div>
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black !my-0" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">Script · YouTube</h1>
        <p class="!my-1 font-medium" style="color: var(--color-primary);">~7 min · three-sided marketplace, contradictory segmentation</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16">
    <div class="prose-factory">

      <div class="card !p-5 my-6" style="background: rgba(236,72,153,0.10); border: 1px solid rgba(236,72,153,0.25);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">📌 How to use this script</h3>
        <p class="!mb-0">YouTube is the perfect example of a marketplace with contradictory interests across sides. The strong piece: <strong>"brilliant implementation ≠ ethical decision"</strong>. And the under-pressure distinction <strong>"consumer vs decider"</strong> in the transplant to children.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[USER]</h2>
      <p>"I'm going to talk about <strong>YouTube</strong>, which I use every day. My primary user is not 'people who watch videos', because that covers 2 billion people. <strong>My primary user is the adult who consumes YouTube as background TV and as an audiovisual search engine</strong>, not as a social network."</p>
      <p>"I choose this user because they sustain YouTube's advertising model: long sessions, recommendations that matter, dense advertising profiles. I'll touch on other users as contrast: creators, children under 13, casual users arriving from links."</p>

      <h2>[SUB-SEGMENTS]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>The passive consumer.</strong> Watches YouTube as TV: leaves autoplay on, values continuous flow, doesn't search actively. Long sessions, almost zero decision-making."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The task consumer.</strong> Comes to YouTube looking for something specific: tutorial, review, explanation. Short and focused session. Key metric: did they find what they were looking for."</li>
        <li>"<strong>The educational consumer.</strong> Sees YouTube as a university: long courses, lectures, recorded podcasts. Medium-to-long sessions, high intentionality."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"I'm going to focus on <strong>the passive consumer</strong>, because it's the sub-segment that generates the most ad revenue, and where recommendation decisions have the largest impact."</p>

      <h2>[ECOSYSTEM]</h2>
      <p>"YouTube plays on three boards simultaneously, and each one has different incentives."</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>Consumer attention</strong>, competing with TikTok, Netflix, Spotify (when it's audio), Twitch, podcasts."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Creator relationship</strong>, where they are YouTube's suppliers. Competing with TikTok, Patreon, Substack, Twitch to retain the people who produce content."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Advertising business</strong>, where they compete with Meta Ads, Google Search Ads, TikTok Ads for brand budgets."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"What's important: <strong>the three sides have incentives that sometimes contradict each other</strong>. More ads lift ad revenue but degrade the consumer. Better payment to creators reduces margin but retains them. An addictive recommendation lifts engagement but can harm the task consumer who just wanted one thing."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Anchor sentence. "The three sides have contradictory incentives". This separates you from the candidate who sees YouTube as a simple single-axis product.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[BRILLIANT IMPLEMENTATION IS NOT ETHICAL DECISION]</h2>
      <p>"Before I propose, an observation. YouTube's recommendation system is <strong>technically brilliant</strong>: it uses deep learning over billions of signals, optimises in real time, predicts engagement with precision that was unimaginable 10 years ago. It's first-class engineering."</p>
      <p>"But <strong>the decision of what to optimise</strong> (aggregate watch time) is a product decision, not a technical one. And that decision, although brilliantly executed, has produced documented side effects: radicalisation of political content, conspiracy tunnels, problematic consumption habits. Brilliant implementation doesn't exempt the optimisation decision from ethical scrutiny."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Anchor sentence. "Brilliant implementation ≠ ethical decision". This sentence marks you as a PM with judgement, not a tech bro. In Stripe it matters.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>[PROPOSAL]</h2>
      <p>"My proposal: <strong>recommendation modes chosen by the user</strong>. Today YouTube implicitly optimises for engagement. My change: the user explicitly chooses what they want from the current session (rest, learn something, search for something specific, discover something new). YouTube adjusts recommendations according to the chosen mode and shows which one it's using."</p>
      <p>"It connects to the passive consumer (my sub-segment) because it gives them control in a channel where today they have none. And it separates interests: in 'rest' mode YouTube can prioritise engagement; in 'learn' mode YouTube should prioritise long-video completion, not jumping across topics."</p>

      <h2>[EDGE CASES]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, extra friction. If I ask the user to choose a mode each session, total engagement drops. Solution: persistent mode with quick switch, not per-session obligation."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, user who never changes mode and stays on 'rest' (which is the highest-engagement mode). Solution: gentle nudges when I detect a pattern ('you're watching tutorials, activate learn mode?')."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, 'learn' mode lowers ad revenue because that's not where premium ads sit. Solution: higher-quality, lower-frequency ads in low-interruption modes, commercially justifiable because it attracts different advertisers."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[RISKS: TIGER + PAPER TIGER]</h2>
      <p>"<strong>🐅 Tiger:</strong> ad revenue in non-engagement modes. The 'learn' or 'search' mode inherently has less ad space than the 'rest' mode. Mitigation: the target isn't revenue per session, it's user retention over the long term. A consumer who trusts YouTube uses more YouTube."</p>
      <p>"<strong>📰 Paper Tiger:</strong> 'TikTok is going to eat YouTube on consumer time'. Looks plausible but isn't true for my sub-segment. TikTok competes for fragmented attention in short sessions. YouTube dominates long sessions with educational content, video podcasts, gaming streams. Two different products in two different attention lengths. The passive YouTube consumer isn't the marginal TikTok user, they're different profiles."</p>

      <h2>[METRICS]</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>Target:</strong> user retention at 12 months per sub-segment. North Star because it measures relational health, not extractive engagement."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Leading:</strong> adoption rate of the chosen mode in first 4 weeks. Target 30%."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Lagging:</strong> aggregate watch time at 12 months. Target stable or slightly positive (the hypothesis is that it doesn't drop even when we change the optimisation)."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Guard rail:</strong> ad revenue per active user. Cannot drop more than 8%. If it does, the model is unsustainable for YouTube as a business."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>[TRANSPLANT]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine: 'OK, now do it for children under 10'."</p>
      <p>"<strong>OK, let me pause. The context changes radically.</strong>"</p>
      <ul>
        <li>"<strong>One</strong>, I assumed the user has authority over their own consumption. For a child under 10, authority is with the parent / carer, not the child. The consumer and the decider are different people, no longer the same."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Two</strong>, I assumed ability to evaluate content. The child cannot judge whether a video is educational, hidden advertising, or problematic. Filtering has to be strict and non-negotiable, not optional."</li>
        <li>"<strong>Three</strong>, I assumed an acceptable advertising model. For under-13s there's regulation (COPPA in the US, similar in Europe). The revenue model has to shift to subscription or strictly regulated ads."</li>
      </ul>
      <p>"With those assumptions broken, my proposal changes. Instead of 'modes chosen by the user', I'd propose <strong>a curated catalogue with time allocated by the parent</strong>. The parent configures which categories are allowed (educational, limited entertainment), how much total time per day, and what signals they receive (what the child watched, for how long). YouTube Kids already exists, but my proposal goes further in granularity of parental control."</p>

      <h2>[IF THEY PUSH BACK]</h2>
      <p>"Imagine: 'you said the parent is the primary user, but if the child doesn't find the product fun, the app gets uninstalled, doesn't the child ultimately decide?'"</p>
      <p>"Good question. Let me distinguish two things I was conflating. <strong>Consumer</strong> is who uses the product, and there the child clearly decides: if they don't have fun, they leave. <strong>Decider</strong> is who buys, installs, maintains, pays, decides to remove the app. And there the parent decides. The design has to serve both, but in different roles: fun and motivating features for the consumer (child), control, peace of mind and reporting features for the decider (parent). Both figures have a vote, it's not just one. <strong>My mistake in the first answer was collapsing both figures into 'primary user'</strong>."</p>

      <div class="card !p-3 my-3" style="background: var(--color-mist); border-left: 3px solid var(--color-stone);">
        <p class="!my-0 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">👀 Pattern 10 in its strongest form. Explicitly acknowledging the mistake ("my mistake was...") demonstrates intellectual honesty without weakness. And the "consumer vs decider" distinction is from formal PM vocabulary for products targeting minors. Stripe knows it.</p>
      </div>

      <hr class="my-10" />

      <div class="card !p-6 my-8" style="background: var(--color-primary-soft);">
        <h3 class="!mt-0">🎯 The three anchor sentences</h3>
        <ol class="!mb-0">
          <li><strong>"The three sides of YouTube have contradictory incentives."</strong></li>
          <li><strong>"Brilliant implementation does not equal ethical decision."</strong></li>
          <li><strong>"Consumer vs decider: two figures, two votes, two designs."</strong></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-3 mt-10">
        <a href="/stripe-mocks/guion/claude-code" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">← Claude Code</a>
        <span style="color: var(--color-stone);">·</span>
        <a href="/stripe-mocks" class="text-sm hover:opacity-80" style="color: var(--color-primary);">Hub</a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</LightLayout>
